  "prompt": "Money laundering has to be illegal, right?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of transactions or financial systems. This illegal activity is used to disguise the true origin of funds derived from criminal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, tax evasion, and other illegal enterprises.\n\nThe illegality of money laundering is rooted in its association with and facilitation of criminal activities. Laws and regulations targeting money laundering have been established globally to combat this practice, with many countries implementing stringent measures to detect, prevent, and prosecute such activities. Prominent international efforts include the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets global standards to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nFor these reasons, money laundering is criminalized, and individuals or entities found guilty of engaging in it can face severe penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture.",
